04894nam a22006375i 9780231550062DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2023009636  a97802315500627 a10.7312/siny192942doi  a(DE-B1597)673023  a(OCoLC)1381094933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aZ480.F53bS56 2023 4aZ480.F53 7aLAN0270002bisacsh04a070.50973/0904223/eng/202306011 aSinykin, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBig Fiction :bHow Conglomeration Changed the Publishing Industry and American Literature /cDan Sinykin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Mass Market (I) How Mass- Market Books Changed Publishing -- t2 Mass Market (II) How the Mass Market Won the World, Lost Its Soul—Then Lost the World -- t3 Trade (I) How Women Resisted Sexism and Reinvented the Novel -- t4 Trade (II) How Literary Writers Embraced Genre -- t5 Nonprofits: How Rebels Found Funding and Rejected New York -- t6 Independents: How W. W. Norton Stayed Free and Housed the Misfits -- tConclusion -- tGlossary of Publishing Figures -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late 1950s, Random House editor Jason Epstein would talk jazz with Ralph Ellison or chat with Andy Warhol while pouring drinks in his office. By the 1970s, editors were poring over profit-and-loss statements. The electronics company RCA bought Random House in 1965, and then other large corporations purchased other formerly independent publishers. As multinational conglomerates consolidated the industry, the business of literature—and literature itself—transformed.Dan Sinykin explores how changes in the publishing industry have affected fiction, literary form, and what it means to be an author. Giving an inside look at the industry’s daily routines, personal dramas, and institutional crises, he reveals how conglomeration has shaped what kinds of books and writers are published. Sinykin examines four different sectors of the publishing industry: mass-market books by brand-name authors like Danielle Steel; trade publishers that encouraged genre elements in literary fiction; nonprofits such as Graywolf that aspired to protect literature from market pressures; and the distinctive niche of employee-owned W. W. Norton. He emphasizes how women and people of color navigated shifts in publishing, arguing that writers such as Toni Morrison allegorized their experiences in their fiction.Big Fiction features dazzling readings of a vast range of novelists—including E. L. Doctorow, Judith Krantz, Renata Adler, Stephen King, Joan Didion, Cormac McCarthy, Chuck Palahniuk, Patrick O’Brian, and Walter Mosley—as well as vivid portraits of industry figures. Written in gripping and lively prose, this deeply original book recasts the past six decades of American fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAuthors and publisherszUnited States. 0aBooks and readingzUnited States. 0aFictionxPublishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFictionxPublishingzUnited States. 0aPublishers and publishingxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aPublishers and publishingxMergerszUnited States. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited StatesxMergers. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Publishing.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7